<chapter xml:id="ch-chapter-title" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this chapter, we give a fairly careful account of the theoretical foundations of integration loosely based on Chapters 13 and 14 of Spivak's <pubtitle>Calculus</pubtitle>.
      In particular, we use <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Gaston_Darboux">Jean-Gaston Darboux's</url> elegant reformulation of <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann">Bernhard Riemann's</url> pioneering theory of integration.
      Thus, this chapter supplements the more conventional account in <url href="https://opentext.uleth.ca/apex-calculus/chapter_integration.html">Chapter 5</url> of <pubtitle>APEX Calculus</pubtitle>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

